Your team is using an AI coding agent (Claude Code with the Temporal Developer Skill installed) to help migrate a long-running Order Fulfillment workflow from an older pattern to use `continue-as-new`. The agent generates the following Go code:

```go
func OrderFulfillmentWorkflow(ctx workflow.Context, orders []Order) error {
    for _, order := range orders {
        if err := processOrder(ctx, order); err != nil {
            return err
        }
    }
    if workflow.GetInfo(ctx).ContinueAsNewSuggested {
        return workflow.NewContinueAsNewError(ctx, OrderFulfillmentWorkflow, []Order{})
    }
    return nil
}
```

A senior engineer reviews this and says the AI-generated code has a critical production flaw that the Temporal Developer Skill should have caught — specifically around workflow determinism and history replay. Which of the following best describes the flaw and why it would cause non-deterministic behavior in production?

Context: The Temporal Developer Skill is documented as providing 'expert-level knowledge of Temporal's programming model — workflow determinism rules, activity patterns, retry policies, error handling, testing strategies, worker configuration, versioning, and common gotchas.'
